@startuml Caching

title High-Level Design: Caching Strategies

skinparam backgroundColor #FAFAFA
skinparam componentStyle rectangle

actor "Client" as client

component "Application\nService" as app #D5E8D4

component "Cache\n(Redis / Memcached)" as cache #FFF2CC {
    storage "In-Memory\nKey-Value Store" as kv
}

database "Primary\nDatabase" as db #DDEEFF

' ─── Cache-Aside (Lazy Loading) ───
note as n1
  **1. Cache-Aside (Lazy Loading)**
  READ:
    1. Check cache → HIT → return data
    2. MISS → read DB → populate cache → return
  WRITE:
    Invalidate / update cache after DB write
end note

' ─── Write-Through ───
note as n2
  **2. Write-Through**
  WRITE:
    Write to cache AND DB synchronously.
  PRO: cache always consistent
  CON: write latency increases
end note

' ─── Write-Back (Write-Behind) ───
note as n3
  **3. Write-Back**
  WRITE:
    Write to cache only → async flush to DB.
  PRO: low write latency
  CON: risk of data loss on crash
end note

' ─── Read-Through ───
note as n4
  **4. Read-Through**
  Cache sits in-line; on MISS cache
  fetches from DB itself.
end note

client --> app   : Request
app    --> cache : 1. Cache lookup
cache  --> app   : HIT → cached data
app    --> db    : MISS → DB query
db     --> app   : DB result
app    --> cache : Populate cache (TTL)
app    --> client : Response

note right of cache
  **Eviction Policies:**
  • LRU – Least Recently Used
  • LFU – Least Frequently Used
  • FIFO – First In First Out
  • TTL – Time To Live expiry

  **Cache Problems:**
  • Cache Stampede (dog-piling)
  • Cache Penetration (non-existent keys)
  • Cache Avalanche (mass expiry)
  • Thundering Herd
end note

note bottom of db
  Always the source of truth.
  Cache is a performance layer only.
end note

@enduml

